Since,<br><br>$$f(m,n,p) = \sum\limits_{i = 0}^p {\left( {\matrix{
   m  \cr 
   i  \cr 

 } } \right)\left( {\matrix{
   {n + i}  \cr 
   p  \cr 

 } } \right)\left( {\matrix{
   {p + n}  \cr 
   {p - i}  \cr 

 } } \right)} $$<br><br>$$ = \sum\limits_{i = 0}^p {{{m!} \over {i!(m - i)!}} \times {{(n + i)!} \over {p!(n + i - p)!}} \times {{(p + n)!} \over {(p - i)!(n + i)!}}} $$<br><br>$$ = {{(n + p)!} \over {p!}}\sum\limits_{i = 0}^p {{}^m{C_i} \times {}^n{C_{p - i}}} $$<br><br>$$ = {}^{n + p}{C_p}{}^{m + n}{C_p}$$<br><br>Since, $$g(m,\,n) = \sum\limits_{p = 0}^{m + n} {{{f(m,n,p)} \over {\left( {\matrix{
   {n + p}  \cr 
   p  \cr 

 } } \right)}}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sum\limits_{p = 0}^{m + n} {{{{}^{n + p}{C_p} \times {}^{m + n}{C_p}} \over {{}^{n + p}{C_p}}}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sum\limits_{p = 0}^{m + n} {{}^{m + n}{C_p}}  = {2^{m + n}}$$<br><br>$$ \therefore $$ $$g(m,n) = g(n,m) = {2^{m + n}}$$, <br><br>and $$g(m,n + 1) = {2^{m + n + 1}} = g(m + 1,n)$$ and <br><br>$$g(2m,2n) = {2^{2(m + n)}} = {({2^{(m + n)}})^2} = {(g(m,n))^2}$$.

